In most SQL databases (PostgreSQL, MySQL, SQL Server, etc.), you can group operations into a transaction. This is to prevent accidental mass deletion - 
it turns out there can be outliers where the "WHERE" clause is dropped. 
Source: https://medium.com/@irinelcristea/the-day-i-deleted-1m-rows-in-production-and-how-sql-saved-me-ab530df09fc1

BEGIN;

DELETE FROM users WHERE active = false;

-- Then check:
SELECT COUNT(*) FROM users;

-- Only if youâ€™re sure:
COMMIT;

-- Or cancel:
ROLLBACK;
